1 (1) Is capable of meeting the needs of the child;
2 (2) Is protective of the child;
3 (3) Does not physically or sexually abuse the child or
4 neglect the child; and
5 (4) Is a person with whom the child is bonded or to whom
6 the child is attached; or
7 (b) Issue an order requiring a child to receive reunification
8 treatment unless:
9 (1) Generally accepted and scientifically valid proof
10 demonstrates that the reunification treatment is:
11 (I) Safe, effective and of therapeutic value; and
12 (II) Will not harm a child; and
13 (2) The reunification treatment is not predicated on
14 isolating a child from a parent who meets the requirements set
15 forth in subparagraphs (1) to (4), inclusive, of paragraph (a) or
16 otherwise prohibiting contact between a child and any such
17 parent.
18 2. As used in this section, “reunification treatment” means a
19 treatment or therapy aimed at reuniting or reestablishing a
20 relationship between a child and an estranged or rejected parent
21 or other family member of the child.
22 Sec. 6. 1. Notwithstanding any other provision of law, in a
23 child custody proceeding in which a parent is alleged to have
24 committed domestic violence or child abuse:
25 (a) Expert evidence relating to alleged domestic violence or
26 child abuse may only be admitted by a professional who possesses
27 demonstrated expertise and substantial clinical experience that are
28 not primarily of a forensic nature;
29 (b) The court shall, in making any finding relating to an
30 allegation of domestic violence or child abuse, consider all
31 relevant and admissible evidence of past domestic violence or child
32 abuse committed by the parent who is the subject of the allegation,
33 including, without limitation, any evidence which indicates that
34 the parent has been:
35 (1) Arrested for or convicted of domestic violence or child
36 abuse; or
37 (2) A party against whom an order for protection,
38 restraining order or injunction in the nature of an order for
39 protection is issued; and
40 (c) The court shall not issue an order to remediate the
41 resistance of a child to have contact with a parent alleged to have
42 committed domestic violence or child abuse unless the order:
43 (1) Primarily addresses the behavior of the parent with
44 whom the child resists contact; and
